1.  TYPE OF DATA

1.1  Parameter/Measurement.  Solar radio flux is measured from the
undisturbed solar surface, developing active regions on the sun and from
short-lived enhancements above the daily level.  Values are recorded for
the actual observed, absolute and adjusted solar flux.

1.2  Unit of Measurement.  Radio flux is measured in 10 to the -22 Joules/
second/square meter/Hertz.

1.3  Data Source.  Data prior to July, 1991 are collected from the radio
telescope at the Canada Institute for Scientific and Technical Information
near Ottawa, Ontario.  Data after July, 1991 are from the Dominion Radio
Astrophysical Observatory in Penticton, British Columbia.

1.4  Data Set Identification.  Solar radio flux from the entire solar disk
is measured at a frequency of 2800 megahertz.  The original data values
have been multiplied by 10 to suppress the decimal point.  The data are
available from the National Research Council of Canada or the National
Geophysical Data Center in Boulder, Colorado.  The NASA Climate Data System
(NCDS) also supports this data set online in Common Data Format.


2.  SPATIAL CHARACTERISTICS

2.1  Spatial Coverage.  The data set covers the entire solar disk.  Solar
flux values represent the undisturbed solar surface, developing active
regions on the sun and short-lived flux anomalies above the daily level.

2.2  Spatial Resolution.  There is no resolution within the disk.


3.  TEMPORAL CHARACTERISTICS

3.1  Temporal Coverage.  The data set covers the period from February 14,
1947 to the present.  The NASA Climate Data System currently supports the
data set through May 31, 1991.  Coverage is continuous from beginning to
end.

3.2  Temporal Resolution.  Solar flux values are measured daily.  Emitted
radio flux level measured at the Ottawa, Ontario telescope was determined
daily at local noon (1700  GMT).  The values measured at the Penticton,
British Columbia telescope are determined daily at 1900 GMT.  Monthly mean
values have also been calculated and are available through the NCDS.


4.  INSTRUMENT DESCRIPTION

4.1  Mission Objectives.  The sun emits radio energy with a slowly varying
intensity.  This varying intensity of solar flux values can be related to
the natural solar cycle and thus corresponding climate on Earth.  Long term
study of solar irradiance can be used to predict total solar irradiance on
Earth and thus associated climate impact.

4.2  Key Satellite Flight Parameters.  N/A

4.3  Principles of Operation.  Each day, radio flux levels at 2800 MHz are
determined at local noon (1700 GMT) at Ottawa or 1900 GMT at Penticton.
Three sets of fluxes are summarized; the observed, the adjusted, and the
absolute.  The final flux values represent the energy flux received by a
detector located at the mean distance between the sun and Earth.

4.4  Instrument Measurement Geometry.  The Ottawa radio telescope measured
solar radio flux at the sun angle at local noon in Ottawa, Canada (1700
GMT) prior to July, 1991.  Data collected after July, 1991 from the
Dominion Radio Astrophysical Observatory telescope are measured at 1900
GMT.  Both telescopes have identical measurement geometry.  The geometry of
the Penticton telescope varies by season.


5.  DATA PROCESSING SEQUENCE

5.1  Processing Steps and Data Sets.  Radio flux originates from the
atmospheric layers high in the sun's chromosphere and low in its corona.
This radio flux varies in response to the number of sun spot groups on the
solar disk.  These emissions come from the undisturbed solar surface, from
developing active regions and from short-lived enhancements above the daily
level.  Daily levels of radio flux are determined at 1700 or 1900 GMT from
a conventional radio telescope.  The values are then corrected to within a
few percentage points for factors such as antenna gain, atmospheric
absorption, solar bursts in progress and background sky temperature.

5.2  Derivation Techniques/Algorithms.  Three sets of fluxes are
summarized; the observed, the adjusted, and the absolute.  Of these three,
the observed numbers are the least refined since they contain fluctuations
as large as 7% that arise from the changing Sun-Earth distance.  The
adjusted flux values have the Sun-Earth variation removed.  The absolute
values carry the error reduction one step further by multiplying each value
0.90 to compensate for uncertainties in antenna gain and in waves reflected
from the ground.

5.3  Special Corrections/Adjustments.  Corrections are made to account for
the changing Sun-Earth distance and for uncertainties in antenna gain and
in waves reflected from ground.

5.4  Processing Changes.  None.


6.  QUALITY ASSESSMENT

6.1  Data Validation by Producer.

6.2  Confidence Level/Accuracy Judgment.  The final solar radio flux values
are accurate to within a few percent of actual values due to such factors
as antenna gain, solar bursts in progress during observation time and
background sky temperature.

6.3  Usage Guidance.  The Penticton Solar Flux data set is used in
conjunction with other solar activity data sets derived from total solar
irradiance instruments on Nimbus-7 and the Solar Maximum Mission.


